		<description><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-size: small;">When I first started making websites I got into the terrible habit of writing my CSS code in long hand, long hand is where you specify each rule to a selector, class or id and so on in a more</span>&#8230;</p>]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-size: small;">When I first started making websites I got into the terrible habit of writing my CSS code in long hand, long hand is where you specify each rule to a selector, class or id and so on in a more broken down anti compressive way.</span><br />
In this example I have written the padding and margin in long hand, see how I&#8217;ve marked up the padding, specifying the measurements top right bottom and left on a new line for each rule.</p>
<h2>Long hand</h2>
<div class="code-wrap">
<pre><code>

selector
{
padding-top: 0;
padding-right: 0;
padding-bottom: 0;
padding-left: 0;

margin-top: 0;
margin-right: 0;
margin-bottom: 0;
margin-left: 0;
}

</code></pre>
</div>
<h2>Short hand</h2>
<p>The short hand is so easy to understand, in layman&#8217;s terms you specify each measurement in a single line after the margin or padding has been specified.</p>
<p>The first unit is top then right, bottom and left, resulting in the 4 units inline closed off with a colon.</p>
<div class="code-wrap">
<pre><code>

selector
{
padding: 0 0 0 0;
Margin: 0 0 0 0;
}

</code></pre>
</div>
<p>And that’s short hand for margins and padding. There are other rules you can use short hand code on so keep an eye out for more short hand code posts in future.</p>
